  "prompt": "How are septums pierced?",
  "response": "Septum piercings are a type of body piercing that goes through the nasal septum, which is the cartilage and tissue that separates the nostrils. Here's a general overview of how septum piercings are typically done:\n\n1. **Preparation:**\n   - The piercer will clean the area to ensure it's free from bacteria.\n   - They might mark the spot where the piercing will be placed to ensure accuracy.\n\n2. **Choosing the Jewelry:**\n   - The piercer will select an appropriate piece of jewelry, usually a circular barbell or a horseshoe ring, made of materials like surgical steel or titanium.\n\n3. **The Piercing Process:**\n   - The piercer will use a sterile, hollow needle to create the piercing. They'll insert the needle through the soft tissue just above the cartilage, known as the \"sweet spot.\"\n   - The jewelry is then inserted through the needle and secured in place.\n\n4. **Aftercare:**\n   - The piercer will provide instructions on how to care for the piercing to prevent infection and promote healing. This usually involves cleaning the piercing regularly with a saline solution and avoiding irritants.\n\n5. **Healing Time:**\n   - The healing time for a septum piercing can vary but typically takes about 6 to 8 weeks.\n\nIt's important to have a septum piercing done by a professional piercer to minimize the risk of complications. They can ensure that the piercing is done correctly and safely.",
